" {MPLTEXT 1 0 30 "2*int(2-y^4 - y^(2/3),y=0..1);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6##\"#7\"\"&" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 
"" 0 "" {TEXT -1 113 "Let's try some \"definite\" integrals with \"ind
efinite\" limits of integration.  For example compute using MAPLE    \+
" }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "int(x^3,x=1..a)" "6#-%$intG6$*$%\"xG\"\"$/F';\"\"\"%
\"aG" }{TEXT -1 5 " .   " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "
" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 15 "In fact try    " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "int
(x^3,x=a..b)" "6#-%$intG6$*$%\"xG\"\"$/F';%\"aG%\"bG" }{TEXT -1 4 " . \+
 " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 228 "This result should be suggestive.  We'll return to it at
 the end of the exercise.  But first let's consider some \"improper in
tegrals.\"   In particular we'll look at some integrals with one, or b
oth, limits of integration being  " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "infinity" "6#%)inf
inityG" }{TEXT -1 16 " .  Recall that " }}{PARA 256 "" 0 "" {XPPEDIT 
18 0 "int(f,x=a..infinity)" "6#-%$intG6$%\"fG/%\"xG;%\"aG%)infinityG" 
}{TEXT -1 22 "   is defined to be   " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "limit(int(f,x=a.
.b),b=infinity)" "6#-%&limitG6$-%$intG6$%\"fG/%\"xG;%\"aG%\"bG/F.%)inf
inityG" }{TEXT -1 4 "   ." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 81 "To demonstra
te this definition perform the following sequences of MAPLE commands.
" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {XPPEDIT 19 1 "int(x^(-2),x=1..a);" "6#-%
$intG6$)%\"xG,$\"\"#!\"\"/F';\"\"\"%\"aG" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 
20 "6#*&,&%\"aG\"\"\"F&!\"\"F&F%F'" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{XPPEDIT 19 1 "limit(int(x^(-2),x = 1 .. a),a=infinity);" "6#-%&limitG
6$-%$intG6$)%\"xG,$\"\"#!\"\"/F*;\"\"\"%\"aG/F1%)infinityG" }}{PARA 
11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#\"\"\"" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{XPPEDIT 19 1 "int(x^(-2),x=1..infinity);" "6#-%$intG6$)%\"xG,$\"\"#!
\"\"/F';\"\"\"%)infinityG" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#\"\"\"" }
}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {XPPEDIT 19 1 "int(1/x,x = 1 .. a);" "6#-%$
intG6$*&\"\"\"F'%\"xG!\"\"/F(;F'%\"aG" }}{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 
0 0 "" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#-%#lnG6#%\"aG" }}}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {XPPEDIT 19 1 "limit(int(1/x,x = 1 .. a),a=infinity)
;" "6#-%&limitG6$-%$intG6$*&\"\"\"F*%\"xG!\"\"/F+;F*%\"aG/F/%)infinity
G" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#%)infinityG" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 ">
 " 0 "" {XPPEDIT 19 1 "int(1/x,x=1..infinity);" "6#-%$intG6$*&\"\"\"F'
%\"xG!\"\"/F(;F'%)infinityG" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#%)infin
ityG" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 260 42 "What is the total area under th
e graph of " }{TEXT -1 3 "   " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "1/x" "6#*&\"\"\"F$%\"xG
!\"\"" }{TEXT -1 5 "   , " }{TEXT 261 41 "above the x-axis, and to the
 right of x=1" }{TEXT -1 3 "?  " }}{PARA 258 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 133 "Wha
t is the total volume of the object gotten from rotating this region a
bout the x-axis?  (WARNING, the \"obvious\" answer is wrong!) " }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 
26 "int(Pi/x^2,x=1..infinity);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#%#Pi
G" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 96 "If \+
you have taken statistics, or probability, you will recognize the foll
owing function.  Define" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {XPPEDIT 19 1 "p:=exp((-x^2)/2)/sqrt(2*Pi);" "6#>%\"
pG*&-%$expG6#*&,$*$%\"xG\"\"#!\"\"\"\"\"F-F.F/-%%sqrtG6#*&F-F/%#PiGF/F
." }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>%\"pG,$*&#\"\"\"\"\"#F(*(-%$expG
6#,$*&F)!\"\"%\"xGF)F0F(F)F'%#PiG#F0F)F(F(" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 375 "It's called the \"normal distribution\" and its graph is the u
sual \"bell shaped\" curve in statistics.  The total area under its gr
aph and above the x-axis is 1,  the area under its graph and between x
=-1 and x=1 is the portion of the total population that is 1 \"standar
d deviation\" form the mean.  Plot the graph with suitable range on x \+
to generate a nice bell shaped curve.  " }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 23 "plot(p,x=-5..5,y=0..1);" }}{PARA 13 "" 1 "" 
